ce:section.ce:para:
The excitation dependant emission property of CQDs and degradation resistant blue emission of CQDs-silica were further utilized to construct CQDs-Terbium–Europium doped silica matrices. Photoluminescence studies of CQDs-Terbium–Europium doped silica matrices having same RE concentration but different CQDs concentration were done to investigate their applicability to construct white light emitting devices (Fig. 8
                     ). Emission spectra show broad blue emission band of CQDs and narrow green-red emissions of rare ions. Due to the intra 4f-4f transitions in Eu3+ and Tb3+, emission bands peaked at 487 nm, 542 nm, 590 nm, 616 nm 651 nm and 698 nm wavelengths are observed. Blue-green emission bands peaked at 487 nm is due to the 5D4→ 7F6,5 magnetic, electric dipole transitions of Tb3+ ions [48–50]. Particularly, the most intense emission of Tb3+ peaked at 542 nm wavelength corresponds to 5D4→ 7F5 transitions having significant magnetic dipole contributions. The remaining peaks at 590 nm (5D0→7F1), 616 nm (5D0→7F2), 651 nm (5D0→7F3) and 698 nm (5D0→7F4) can be attributed to the transitions of Europium ions [51,52]. An evident spectral dip around 417 nm was obtained due to the spectral overlap of luminescent bands of CQDs with the excitation peak of Eu3+ions which can be ascribed due to the 7F0→5D3 transitions in Eu3+ ions. This is a clear evidence of energy transfer between CQDs and Eu3+ ions. With the same concentration of RE, green-red emissions of Tb3+ and Eu3+ ions are enhanced in A1 due to the presence of higher concentration of carbon quantum dots. Significant optical amplification observed here is due to direct energy transfer from CQDs to Tb3+ and Eu3+ ions (Fig. 9
                     ). Thus, by varying the excitation wavelength and concentration of CQDs, a fine tuning of blue-green-red emissions is achieved. Generally, Tb3+ based materials glow green light due to most intense emissions (5D4→ 7F5) at 542 nm at prominent excitation wavelength of 370 nm [49]. Similarly, Eu3+ based materials are well known as red emitting phosphors owing to intense red colour emissions (613 nm wavelength) due to 5D0→7F2 transitions at 393 nm excitation wavelength [51]. As RE ions are known to show sharp intense emissions at only particular excitations, the existence of all Eu3+ emission curves at excitation wavelengths other than its prominent excitations illustrates the energy transfer between CQDs and RE. Though 380 nm wavelength is not a prominent excitation wavelength for Tb3+ and Eu3+, green-red emissions of comparable intensity are achieved in both samples. Due to the spectral overlap and vicinity of luminescent centres efficient Forster resonance energy transfer occurs. By the incorporation into a rigid matrix, vicinity of donor-acceptor (CQDs-RE3+) comes to a close distance (<10 nm) which enhances the energy transfer routes.
